<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900816-0004</DOCNO><DOCID>900816-0004.</DOCID><HL>   Teledyne Ex-Official   Charged in Scheme   To Defraud the Navy</HL><DATE>08/16/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16</SO><CO>   TDY</CO><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   NEW YORK -- In federal court in Manhattan, the formerpresident of a Teledyne Inc. division was charged with makingfalse statements to the Defense Department in connection withan alleged scheme to defraud the Navy on a helicoptercontract.   The defendant, Cirino Giampapa, 69 years old, ofMassapequa, N.Y., was president of Teledyne Hydra-Power, adivision of the parent company's Teledyne Industries Inc.unit. In a settlement with the Defense Department, the unitlast year paid $11.9 million to cover overcharges stemmingfrom the scheme, as well as interest and penalties, the U.S.attorney's office in Manhattan said.</LP><TEXT>   Walter Bonner, an attorney for Mr. Giampapa, could not bereached for comment.   Avraham Moskowitz, the assistant U.S. attorney in chargeof the case, said Teledyne Hydra-Power submitted false claimstotaling $4.5 million between 1980 and 1986. The allegedscheme involved inflating the number of hours worked. Thefigures were provided to the Defense Department and to itsgeneral contractors to justify prices charged by the Teledynedivision for helicopter parts it made.   A Teledyne spokesman said the company's auditing staffuncovered the problem in 1986, which was then flagged to theDefense and Justice departments.   The U.S. attorney's office said that Michael Rosenberg,41, of Suffern, N.Y., a former controller at TeledyneHydra-Power, pleaded guilty to one count of conspiring todefraud the U.S. in connection with the alleged scheme.Morton Baine, 54, of New Rochelle, N.Y., also a formercontroller at the division, was charged with participating inthe alleged conspiracy.   Carl Bernstein, an attorney for Mr. Baine, said his clientpleaded innocent.   Elkan Abramowitz, an attorney for Mr. Rosenberg, couldn'tbe reached for comment. The U.S. attorney's office said Mr.Rosenberg's sentencing is set for Oct. 17 before U.S. JudgeVincent Broderick.</TEXT></DOC>